   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1831-01_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">
                     <choice>
                        <orig>Edgeworth's Town</orig>
                        <reg>Edgeworthstown</reg>
                     </choice>
                  </placeName>
                  <date when="1813-01-17">
                     <choice>
                        <orig>Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>.</orig>
                        <reg>January</reg>
                     </choice> 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1813.</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileJ1">Sir,</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               We have just <choice>
                  <orig>
                     <unclear>rec</unclear>
                     <hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>received</reg>
               </choice> a copy of a second part<lb/>
               of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LeadM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Leadbeaters</persName>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Cotta1">Cottage dialogues</title> which<lb/>
               are <hi rend="underline">admirable</hi>. Instead of falling <choice>
                  <orig>of</orig>
                  <reg>off</reg>
               </choice> as second<lb/>
               parts to popular works too frequently do<lb/>
               this in over unanimous opinion far <choice>
                  <orig>ex=<lb/>
               cels</orig>
                  <reg>excels</reg>
               </choice> the first part equally well adapted<lb/>
               to the moral purposes for which it is <choice>
                  <orig>in=<lb/>
               tended</orig>
                  <reg>intended</reg>
               </choice> and surpassing in <del/>
               <lb/>
               interest &amp; pathos - some of the scenes are<lb/>
               exquisitely pathetic &amp; as my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> has<lb/>
               just written to tell her nothing since the<lb/>
               time of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RamsA1">
                  <unclear>Ramsays</unclear>
               </persName>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Gentl1">Gentle Shepherd</title> has<lb/>
               appeared so truly pastoral.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am anxious to make you fully and<lb/>
               early aware that this <hi rend="underline">second part of</hi>
               <lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Cotta1">
                  <hi rend="underline">Cottage dialogues</hi>
               </title> has nothing to do with<lb/>
               those higher life dialogues which I <choice>
                  <orig>men=<lb/>
               tioned</orig>
                  <reg>mentioned</reg>
               </choice> to you some time ago &amp; which I<lb/>
               desired you would judge of for yourself<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1831-01_page02.jpg"/>
               and not take it for granted that we <choice>
                  <orig>
                     <unclear>recommend</unclear>
                     <lb/>
               ed</orig>
                  <reg>recommended</reg>
               </choice> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LeadM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                  <unclear>Leadbeater</unclear>
               </persName> has she tells me sold<lb/>
               <del>4000</del>
               <lb/>
               "To <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CummX1">
                  <unclear>Cummins</unclear>
               </persName> the liberty of printing 4000 copies<lb/>
               "<unclear>extending</unclear> them to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> for 40 Guineas<lb/>
               - Poor woman she has sold them like a<lb/>
               goose - you would certainly have been more<lb/>
               liberal - and why she did not apply to you<lb/>
               I cannot guess - I hope to Heaven that you<lb/>
               did not <hi rend="underline">refuse</hi> them in consequence of<lb/>
               what I wrote to you - Pray write as soon as<lb/>
               you can &amp; let me know whether she applied<lb/>
               to you? -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               She has reserved the copyright to herself -<lb/>
               - she wishes to know how to enter her<lb/>
               works at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Stationers-Hall_ENK">stationers Hall</placeName> - Tell me or tell<lb/>
               her - I believe the book is not yet <choice>
                  <orig>pub=<lb/>
               lished</orig>
                  <reg>published</reg>
               </choice> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Thank you my dear sir for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Rejec1">Rejected Addresses</title>
               <lb/>
               which have amused us much - my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName>
               <lb/>
               says they are the best things which have<lb/>
               appeared since the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Rolli1">
                  <unclear>Rolliad</unclear>
               </title> &amp; the <unclear>Deaboliad</unclear>
               <lb/>
               - I had a letter from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Walter Scott</persName> yesterday<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1831-01_page03.jpg"/>
               who says the very same thing.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               We have not yet heard from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CummX1">
                  <unclear>Cummins</unclear>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
               of the arrival of my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">fathers</persName>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Lette4">paper on wheel<lb/>
               carriages</title> or of the other things you mention<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am glad <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                  <unclear>Miles</unclear>
               </persName> &amp; you liked the<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>plumbs</orig>
                  <reg>plums</reg>
               </choice> - I hope you are now quite well<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Your faithful <choice>
                  <orig>serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>servant</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  This <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LeadM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Leadbeater</persName> is a sad goose -<lb/>
                  She<lb/>
                  has disposed of a little parcel at <unclear/>
                  <lb/>
                  more, a parcel of glass - I am <unclear/>
                  <lb/>
                  g<unclear/> that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CummX1">
                     <unclear>Cummins</unclear>
                  </persName> will <unclear>gain</unclear> by<lb/>
                  <unclear/>
                  <lb/>
                  rather than some <unclear/> fellows -<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  Pray when you work let us know<lb/>
                  how <unclear>Rookeby</unclear> succeeds - to <unclear/>
                  <unclear/> are<lb/>
                  excellent, free from affectation, full of matter<lb/>
                  <del/>
                  <add>told</add> in the best manners -<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  As <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> has a <unclear>quiet</unclear> regard for you, I beg you<lb/>
                  will point out for her the impropriety of<lb/>
                  sending me &amp; laughing at me! - A miserable<lb/>
                  epigram in her <unclear/>
                  <del/> appeared in a<lb/>
                  Dublin newspaper; - this she would insist upon<lb/>
                  if was my writing; and in consequence<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1831-01_page04.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>she <hi rend="underline">roasted</hi> me continually - I apply to you</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>for <unclear>receipts</unclear>, as if is void, that you wrote the</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>following epigram on her undutiful conduct</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>What filial piety <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> boasts!</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>Medea boiled her she, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> - roasts.</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">RLE</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JohnM2">Miss <unclear>Malan</unclear> Johnson</persName> v G</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#St-Pauls-Churchyard_ENK">S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Pauls <choice>
                           <orig>Chy<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                           </orig>
                           <reg>Churchyard</reg>
                        </choice>
                     </placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
